article.description: Rasheed Wallace and Derek Anderson scored 26 points apiece as the Trail Blazers defeated the Magic for the eighth straight time, 98-84.
article.headline: Magic's Hill sits out most of game with sore foot
article.linkText: Blazers turn to Anderson, who delivers W over Magic
article.story:
PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- The Portland Trail Blazers, a talent-laden team with no true go-to guy, might have found their man.
Anderson

Derek Anderson scored 26 points in his second game after missing four with a concussion as Portland beat the Orlando Magic 98-84 on Wednesday night to win consecutive games for the first time this season. Anderson scored 28 points last week against the Los Angeles Clippers in his return to the lineup, and a Blazers team that was in disarray during the four games Anderson missed suddenly looks like a force. "When we execute like we did tonight, we look a lot better and we have a lot more fun,'' Anderson said. "We had to play together to put these guys away.'' Rasheed Wallace had 26 points and 14 rebounds to break out of a three-game slump, and Scottie Pippen added 13 points and five assists for the Blazers. "It was a breakout game for Rasheed,'' Blazers coach Maurice Cheeks said. "He got out of his slump, but we expected that to happen.'' Said Anderson: "I didn't know he was in a slump, but I've been messed up in the head.'' Orlando's Tracy McGrady led all scorers with 33 points, the seventh consecutive game he's scored at least 30 -- a franchise record -- and the ninth time overall this year. "It was a tough one for us,'' Orlando coach Doc Rivers said. "We took way too many jump shots, then stood around and watched too much. You just felt that at sometime the dam would break.'' Guard Damon Stoudamire, who did not play in the Blazers' last game after getting benched, did not start and was a non-factor in 14 minutes. He was scoreless on 0-for-3 shooting with three rebounds and two assists. "I think sometimes we get caught up in him making shots and it appears he's not playing a good game,'' Cheeks said. "I think sometimes that's a mistake on our part. He ran the club and he defended up the court, which we asked him to do.'' Mike Miller scored 12 points for the Magic, who fell to 2-3 on their six-game road trip. They shot just 36.5 percent from the floor and were 20 points below their league-leading 104.1 average. "We played extremely hard,'' McGrady said. "But just playing hard ain't going to win any ballgames. I got tired in the second half and it showed on my jumper.'' Orlando forward Grant Hill, who missed Sunday's game at Sacramento with soreness in his troublesome left ankle, started but did not play again after nine minutes of action. Team officials described the move as precautionary. Hill scored two points on 1-of-4 shooting. "He told me in the first quarter that his foot was sore so I took him out,'' Rivers said. "He really wanted to play again, but I'd rather drop some games and keep it going because once he gets over this hurdle he'll be fine for the rest of the year. There's no reason to rush this.'' The game also marked the return of Shawn Kemp to the Rose Garden. Kemp forfeited several million dollars of his guaranteed contract with the Blazers during the offseason for a chance to play elsewhere after two unproductive seasons in Portland. That included a stint in drug rehabilitation and a suspension for failing to follow the terms of his aftercare program. Kemp started for the Magic and scored 12 points on 6-of-9 shooting with seven rebounds. The Blazers took a 46-35 halftime lead thanks mostly to 56.8 percent shooting and a double-teaming defense that forced McGrady into a 4-of-12 effort for just 11 points. "He still got his numbers, but I really thought we did a good job of really forcing him to have to get his numbers and keeping the other guys from getting so involved,'' said Pippen, who defended McGrady along with Bonzi Wells and Ruben Patterson. "We just tried to keep a fresh body on him and make him work. He's a very good young talent.'' Orlando shot just 38.5 percent from the floor in the first half, perhaps showing the effects of playing its fifth game in seven nights, all on the West Coast.

Game notes
Orlando's road trip concludes Friday at Indiana. Portland was coming off a four-day layoff, its second-longest of the season. The Blazers have five days off around Christmas and the All-Star game. ... Portland is in a stretch of seven out of eight games at home. ... The Blazers have won seven straight against the Magic. Orlando's last win was March 20, 1998. The Magic's last win in Portland was Dec. 2, 1997.
